because it obviously was a moment where people
were really engaged with what was going on

00:15:16.230 --> 00:15:20.270
and they wanted to pay attention to Jennifer
Hudson on stage.

00:15:20.270 --> 00:15:27.770
So, we don't want to be too broad and say
that "OK, if it's a show and everybody's talking

00:15:27.770 --> 00:15:31.290
about it, then that's a successful show,"
because that's not the case. There's certainly

00:15:31.290 --> 00:15:37.740
programs out there where people are not talking
about it during those shows. It also is an

00:15:37.740 --> 00:15:40.800
opportunity to tell you when something's not
going right in a show.

00:15:40.800 --> 00:15:44.550
So, this is an example from the Emmy's last
year. I don't know how many of you saw this,

00:15:44.550 --> 00:15:50.029
but the Emmytones were these little interstitial
songs that were being sung throughout. And

00:15:50.029 --> 00:15:56.240
the Twitter mentions were universally negative,
right? So, here's an opportunity for a producer

00:15:56.240 --> 00:15:58.100
to say, "Oh, my God. This is not working."

00:15:58.100 --> 00:16:02.660
This is a live show. They could have pulled
these guys right off the air. So, that instant

00:16:02.660 --> 00:16:09.020
feedback can really guide you and give you
some important feedback and impact the content

00:16:09.020 --> 00:16:16.839
of your programming. The second piece is interactivity.
So, the idea of interacting, both on television

00:16:16.839 --> 00:16:19.730
and on secondary screens, is not new.

00:16:19.730 --> 00:16:25.310
It's been around since--. This is an example
from 1996 with WebTV. But there are just so

00:16:25.310 --> 00:16:30.880
many more options to interact with programming.
So, this is an example of the Super Bowl in

00:16:30.880 --> 00:16:36.970
Mike's living room. This is--. He's got his
TV open, his iPad with IntoNow up there. He's

00:16:36.970 --> 00:16:42.370
got his mobile device. And his computer is
following the Brand Bowl to see which commercials

00:16:42.370 --> 00:16:44.980
are winning and which aren't.

00:16:44.980 --> 00:16:50.480
There's lots of different ways to connect
with programming today. And it's very distracting.

00:16:50.480 --> 00:16:54.920
There's no doubt about it. And it's also so
fragmented, right? It would be really easy

00:16:54.920 --> 00:16:59.660
if we knew that everybody that wasn't paying
attention in a commercial break on TV was

00:16:59.660 --> 00:17:01.560
going to the same place on their phone.

00:17:01.560 --> 00:17:07.230
And then, we'll just reach them there, right?
But there's just so many distractions. But

00:17:07.230 --> 00:17:12.480
it's a really good example of how we experience
TV today. So, we look at TV and think of TV

00:17:12.480 --> 00:17:17.120
as more of a cross-channel experience. It's
not just the experience of watching TV on

00:17:17.120 --> 00:17:20.600
the big screen. But there's more ways to experience
the programming.

00:17:20.600 --> 00:17:25.689
So, 40 percent of web owners use their phone
daily while watching TV. So, you assume these

00:17:25.689 --> 00:17:29.160
40 percent of people are just distracted from
our television messages 'cause most likely,

00:17:29.160 --> 00:17:33.450
they're turning away during those commercial
breaks, rather than during the programming.

00:17:33.450 --> 00:17:38.200
So, from a marketer's standpoint, if we know
40 percent of our audience is distracted,

00:17:38.200 --> 00:17:42.320
we need to figure out a way to market it to
those people so that our message is getting

00:17:42.320 --> 00:17:44.110
through to them.

00:17:44.110 --> 00:17:48.559
So is it hurting advertising? Of course it's
hurting advertising without a doubt. So what

00:17:48.559 --> 00:17:53.630
we did at Hill Holiday is we commissioned
a study. And we wanted to see if there was

00:17:53.630 --> 00:18:03.281
a way for us to build back, recall, and preference
for a commercial by doing something in the

00:18:03.281 --> 00:18:07.640
digital environment. So, we went in with the
questions: "Would you recommend it to your

00:18:07.640 --> 00:18:08.640
friends?"

00:18:08.640 --> 00:18:12.470
We showed them clips of the movie trailer,
"Friends with Kids." "Would you watch it yourself

00:18:12.470 --> 00:18:17.630
and can you recall key facts from the trailer?"
And so, our methodologies, we had three test

00:18:17.630 --> 00:18:22.850
groups. We had did a simulation of a two-screen
experience. So, one group had only saw the

00:18:22.850 --> 00:18:24.330
commercial on the primary screen.

00:18:24.330 --> 00:18:28.740
They did not have a secondary device in their
hand. The second group saw the commercial

00:18:28.740 --> 00:18:33.680
on the TV screen and had a secondary device,
but saw a different creative when they went

00:18:33.680 --> 00:18:38.880
on to their secondary device during the commercial
break. And the third group saw the commercial

00:18:38.880 --> 00:18:44.230
on the TV and then saw a synced ad, so the
same creative or creative messaging on their

00:18:44.230 --> 00:18:48.590
secondary device when they were distracted
from the main screen.

00:18:48.590 --> 00:18:54.540
And what we found is, obviously, the group
that didn't have any distraction, that only

00:18:54.540 --> 00:18:58.460
saw the commercial on the primary screen and
was not distracted with a secondary device,

00:18:58.460 --> 00:19:03.200
had the highest recall and the highest preference.
In the second group that was distracted and

00:19:03.200 --> 00:19:08.970
saw a different creative, the recall and preference
dropped eight percent and seventeen percent,

00:19:08.970 --> 00:19:10.080
respectively.

00:19:10.080 --> 00:19:16.500
And then, in that third group, where they
saw a synced ad--so, a "Friends with Kids"

00:19:16.500 --> 00:19:20.920
ad on their secondary device while it was
playing on the main screen--that recall and

00:19:20.920 --> 00:19:25.440
preference went back up almost to the levels
of that primary screen group. So, what that

00:19:25.440 --> 00:19:30.110
tell us is we need to find a way to market
to this group that's distracted from the TV

00:19:30.110 --> 00:19:31.110
screen.

00:19:31.110 --> 00:19:35.300
And the challenge with that is, like I said
before, they're not all in the same place.

00:19:35.300 --> 00:19:39.470
Some of them are on their email. Some of them
are doing companion content to what they're

00:19:39.470 --> 00:19:44.170
watching on TV. But they're in a lot of different
places. And so, we're working out to figure

00:19:44.170 --> 00:19:48.560
out what are those places and where do we
need to be and how can we create that messaging

00:19:48.560 --> 00:19:51.020
so that our message is getting through.

00:19:51.020 --> 00:19:52.020
[pause]

00:19:52.020 --> 00:19:56.730
So, we're fighting for attention. And we'll
continue to figure out how to get through

00:19:56.730 --> 00:20:02.630
with all these distractions. The third piece
is portability. So, the idea of TV everywhere.

00:20:02.630 --> 00:20:07.690
There's so many different devices you can
get your content--on your main screen, on

00:20:07.690 --> 00:20:12.750
your computer, on your phone, on your tablet
through apps, and all different kinds of sites.

00:20:12.750 --> 00:20:20.530
So, your TV everywhere is something that we
have to contend with as well. This is an example

00:20:20.530 --> 00:20:25.810
of the XFINITY iPad app. It basically acts
as your remote control. You can switch channels

00:20:25.810 --> 00:20:32.040
from it. You can get recommendations from
friends. You can try out new programming.

00:20:32.040 --> 00:20:36.390
It really is a control over your whole television
experience. And it's starting to bring some

00:20:36.390 --> 00:20:38.810
of these capabilities together.

00:20:38.810 --> 00:20:40.110
[pause]

00:20:40.110 --> 00:20:43.550
You can just click on, they'll show you top
picks. So, you're getting it sorted by what

00:20:43.550 --> 00:20:46.780
people are watching, what people think is
great that's out there. So, it gives you a

00:20:46.780 --> 00:20:52.950
chance to sample new programming. So, with
all these things out there, we think it's

00:20:52.950 --> 00:20:57.670
important that TV not be considered a traditional
medium--that it's considered a new medium--and

00:20:57.670 --> 00:21:02.500
that you really need to plan it and market
it differently than we have in the past.

00:21:02.500 --> 00:21:06.730
And so, that's why we wrote the book. [laughs]
We wrote the book as a guide for marketers

00:21:06.730 --> 00:21:11.540
because there were so many questions on how
to navigate this space. And when you look

00:21:11.540 --> 00:21:16.710
at the literal definition of social TV, it's
the convergence of social media with television.

00:21:16.710 --> 00:21:20.920
But social TV has sort of become a catch-all
for all technologies and all things that are

00:21:20.920 --> 00:21:21.920
impacting television.

00:21:21.920 --> 00:21:27.750
And we get into a lot of that in the book.
There's chapters in there on the backchannel,

00:21:27.750 --> 00:21:35.050
on bridge content, on social TV guides, on
addressable TV, all the things that are providing

00:21:35.050 --> 00:21:40.660
new marketing opportunities for our clients.
And so the process of going through writing

00:21:40.660 --> 00:21:46.440
the book, we interviewed 75 people for the
