00:23:37.770 --> 00:23:42.950
so rapidly. But in chapter eleven, we talk
about a new planning model. So, one of the

00:23:42.950 --> 00:23:46.660
next questions we get is, "OK. All this stuff
is going on and how is that changing your

00:23:46.660 --> 00:23:48.710
job? What are you doing differently?"

00:23:48.710 --> 00:23:53.731
So, Mike and I worked on this new planning
model. And we call it our "watch model." And

00:23:53.731 --> 00:23:58.890
basically, there's five key things that we
look at. And the first is widening our inputs.

00:23:58.890 --> 00:24:04.809
So, from a TV perspective, we use Neilsen
and MRI/Simmons and have used them for years

00:24:04.809 --> 00:24:09.880
as the source to figure out where is our target
watching and where should we be advertising.

00:24:09.880 --> 00:24:13.760
But now there's so many more data points out
there that we need to take into consideration

00:24:13.760 --> 00:24:19.549
as we're looking at what programs we should
buying for our clients. But this isn't easy,

00:24:19.549 --> 00:24:27.130
right? So, it costs a lot of money to buy
into all of these research companies. So,

00:24:27.130 --> 00:24:31.840
it's challenging, but we're doing our best
to evaluate all of the different research

00:24:31.840 --> 00:24:36.960
companies that are out there to make sure
that we are understanding where our targets

00:24:36.960 --> 00:24:39.530
are and where these influential people are.

00:24:39.530 --> 00:24:44.390
Because as I talked about before, we've been
buying in impressions in television for years,

00:24:44.390 --> 00:24:48.380
but social impressions and the impact that
social impressions can have on your brand

00:24:48.380 --> 00:24:52.410
are probably more valuable. They're smaller
in number, but they're very valuable. And

00:24:52.410 --> 00:24:56.559
we need to know who those people are and what
they're saying about us and how we can market

00:24:56.559 --> 00:24:58.760
appropriately to them.

00:24:58.760 --> 00:25:02.100
The second one is being able to adjust in
real-time. So, my examples from a content

00:25:02.100 --> 00:25:06.970
standpoint from television programming is
we're getting this instant feedback. We need

00:25:06.970 --> 00:25:11.280
to make sure that we're flexible enough on
the agency side to be able to react to it.

00:25:11.280 --> 00:25:17.560
So, whether that's changing things creatively
or moving units from certain shows to others,

00:25:17.560 --> 00:25:21.581
we need to make sure that we're structured
in a way that we can react that way. And we're

00:25:21.581 --> 00:25:27.630
working on it. I think that we're set up more
and more and clients understand that they're

00:25:27.630 --> 00:25:29.559
going to get this feedback instantly.

00:25:29.559 --> 00:25:34.140
And they're gonna need to make decisions more
quickly. So, we're working on being able to

00:25:34.140 --> 00:25:39.890
do that as well. The third is teaming up.
And I'm sure you've heard this before, but

00:25:39.890 --> 00:25:44.320
it's pretty important. And that is that all
of the departments need to work more closely

00:25:44.320 --> 00:25:50.240
together. Not just within media. Not just
digital and TV and planning.

00:25:50.240 --> 00:25:56.261
But creative and production need to be part
of the mix as well. And so, we're structured--.

00:25:56.261 --> 00:26:01.881
Hill Holiday is a fully-integrated agency,
so we're structured in a way that this is

00:26:01.881 --> 00:26:05.350
easier 'cause we're all in the same building.
But we also have clients who are media only

00:26:05.350 --> 00:26:09.700
and we need to work with other agencies and
we need to make sure that this happens.

00:26:09.700 --> 00:26:14.610
Because when we find that all of the teams
are working together and the creative is part

00:26:14.610 --> 00:26:18.840
of the media decision from the beginning and
media is involved in creatives being developed,

00:26:18.840 --> 00:26:27.000
that ultimately we have a much stronger program
in the end. Converging media is really about

00:26:27.000 --> 00:26:31.600
thinking about television as this cross-channel
experience that in planning television and

00:26:31.600 --> 00:26:34.980
planning television GRPs, we're not just planning
for the TV screen.

00:26:34.980 --> 00:26:38.920
So, as we're looking at it, we're really looking
at all of these other environments as part

00:26:38.920 --> 00:26:46.900
of the TV experience because people are experiencing
TV across platforms, not just on one platform.

00:26:46.900 --> 00:26:51.560
And finally, is content and making sure that
everybody focuses on content first. Because

00:26:51.560 --> 00:26:58.150
no matter what great, cool technology is developed,
if the initial content is not good, then people

00:26:58.150 --> 00:26:59.950
aren't gonna wanna do all these other things
around it.

00:26:59.950 --> 00:27:03.370
They're not gonna wanna play games around
it. They're not gonna wanna talk about it.

00:27:03.370 --> 00:27:07.340
They're not gonna wanna sync up and get cool
information about it. And all that stuff just

00:27:07.340 --> 00:27:11.230
doesn't matter, so we wanna make sure that
the content comes first, both from the programming

00:27:11.230 --> 00:27:17.190
side and even from the agency side, when we're
creating campaigns for our clients. We're

00:27:17.190 --> 00:27:20.660
always thinking about what are the new things
that we could be doing. But ultimately, the

00:27:20.660 --> 00:27:23.980
creative messaging in that has to be right
first.

