more time-consuming for us to try and negotiate

00:31:43.700 --> 00:31:44.950
every single deal separately.

00:31:44.950 --> 00:31:53.270
So, if we're doing a deal with NBC and we
wanna look at check-ins and all other kinds

00:31:53.270 --> 00:31:59.280
of things, it would be great if NBC came to
us with a platform that was television plus

00:31:59.280 --> 00:32:06.070
"GetGlue" plus "Viggle" plus what they're
doing on whichever website, whichever show

00:32:06.070 --> 00:32:10.650
that it is, so that we can evaluate it as
a total platform.

00:32:10.650 --> 00:32:17.140
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: Good. And part and parcel
to that, when you, as an agency, don't have

00:32:17.140 --> 00:32:19.750
everything and you're working with other agencies--

00:32:19.750 --> 00:32:20.750
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: Mm-hmm.

00:32:20.750 --> 00:32:24.640
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: how do you manage that?
How does it work? Who takes the lead?

00:32:24.640 --> 00:32:28.210
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: I mean, I think we have
to work together. So, if we're putting a plan

00:32:28.210 --> 00:32:35.799
together with another agency--a media plan--for
our clients, we, the idea could come through

00:32:35.799 --> 00:32:40.620
either through a digital group or through
a TV group. But we have to figure out how

00:32:40.620 --> 00:32:42.600
to work together to negotiate it.

00:32:42.600 --> 00:32:46.929
So, that's where that territorial piece I
talked about comes into play, is you really

00:32:46.929 --> 00:32:53.049
can't be territorial in a situation like that.
Our clients don't want us to be, and get frustrated

00:32:53.049 --> 00:32:58.950
when we are. They just want us to figure it
out. So, the lead tends to come from either

00:32:58.950 --> 00:33:03.830
where the idea came from or where the bulk
of the money is. And that tends to drive the

00:33:03.830 --> 00:33:04.830
negotiation.

00:33:04.830 --> 00:33:10.429
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: OK. Do I have some questions
from the audience there?

00:33:10.429 --> 00:33:16.360
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: [ whispers indistinctly
].

00:33:16.360 --> 00:33:27.660
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: Anybody? Anyone out there?
Here we go.

00:33:27.660 --> 00:33:30.309
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: Yeah.

00:33:30.309 --> 00:33:32.298
&gt;&gt;Female #1: I saw that you mentioned the
study that you did--

00:33:32.298 --> 00:33:33.298
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: Mm-hmm.

00:33:33.298 --> 00:33:34.298
&gt;&gt;Female #1: where people who saw complementary
ads online--

00:33:34.298 --> 00:33:35.298
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: Mm-hmm.

00:33:35.298 --> 00:33:36.298
&gt;&gt;Female #1: while you're watching TV where
the brand recall was almost as high as the

00:33:36.298 --> 00:33:37.298
undistracted.

00:33:37.298 --> 00:33:38.298
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: Yeah.

00:33:38.298 --> 00:33:39.298
&gt;&gt;Female #1: Have you seen any examples of
advertisers that they're doing that well?

00:33:39.298 --> 00:33:40.298
Or, having the ability--?

00:33:40.298 --> 00:33:41.298
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: So, I think it's just starting.
So, we're working with some companies in the

00:33:41.298 --> 00:33:42.298
synced ads space. So, SecondScreen Networks
is one of the companies that's out there that

00:33:42.298 --> 00:33:44.799
Hill Holiday has a partnership with. They're
part of our Beacon Program, which is a program

00:33:44.799 --> 00:33:50.179
for start-ups, where we help guide them and
test out their technologies and hopefully

00:33:50.179 --> 00:33:52.700
find ways to sell them through to our clients.

00:33:52.700 --> 00:33:57.990
So, SecondScreen is a company that's building
an ad network to try and create this synced

00:33:57.990 --> 00:34:03.480
ad experience. They've done some stuff. I
think it was with Lincoln Mercury with one

00:34:03.480 --> 00:34:08.970
of the NBC cable networks that was pretty
successful. So, I think as we're doing some

00:34:08.970 --> 00:34:13.190
testing to see if this environment works,
you'll see more stuff happening in this space.

00:34:13.190 --> 00:34:17.629
&gt;&gt;Female #1: And how is, the people sign up
for the agency site as well--

00:34:17.629 --> 00:34:18.629
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: Mm-hmm?

00:34:18.629 --> 00:34:23.240
&gt;&gt;Female #1: so how are you allocating budgets
between--and I know it has to be territorial--

00:34:23.240 --> 00:34:24.240
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: Mm-hmm.

00:34:24.240 --> 00:34:27.639
&gt;&gt;Female #1: is that a joint budget, or is
it a TV budget or a digital budget?

00:34:27.639 --> 00:34:31.809
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: You know, I get asked that
question a lot. It's sort of--. We have a

00:34:31.809 --> 00:34:35.509
budget. And we may have a TV budget and a
digital budget. And as we're working through

00:34:35.509 --> 00:34:39.339
these plans, we figure it out as we go along,
whether it's gonna come out of the TV budget

00:34:39.339 --> 00:34:44.320
or the digital budget. It depends what's part
of the deal.

00:34:44.320 --> 00:34:51.139
So, if it's full episode play or digital video,
it tends to come out of the TV budget. If

00:34:51.139 --> 00:34:57.039
it's some of these other things, it may come
out of the digital budget. But we try not

00:34:57.039 --> 00:35:01.900
to keep the budgets so siloed, so that we
have the opportunity to evaluate plans like

00:35:01.900 --> 00:35:04.319
this and we have the money to be able to do
it.

00:35:04.319 --> 00:35:05.319
[pause]

00:35:05.319 --> 00:35:09.390
It also helps to try and build these plans
before the budgets are allocated, so that

00:35:09.390 --> 00:35:13.119
we can go to the client and say, "This is
what we wanna do," and it gets taken out of

00:35:13.119 --> 00:35:14.210
the overall budget.

00:35:14.210 --> 00:35:15.310
&gt;&gt;Female #1: Great.

00:35:15.310 --> 00:35:16.400
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: Umm.

00:35:16.400 --> 00:35:17.500
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: Someone at the mic.

00:35:17.500 --> 00:35:18.500
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: Yeah.

00:35:18.500 --> 00:35:19.500
&gt;&gt;Male #1: Hi, Stacey. I'm Mark.

00:35:19.500 --> 00:35:20.500
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: Hi.

00:35:20.500 --> 00:35:21.539
&gt;&gt;Male #1: I have a variation of the same
question.

00:35:21.539 --> 00:35:22.539
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: Yeah.

00:35:22.539 --> 00:35:27.339
&gt;&gt;Male #1: I've noticed a lot of programs
are now inviting their viewers to go to their

00:35:27.339 --> 00:35:31.460
website and download a synchronized application.
I was watching "The Walking Dead" on Sunday.

00:35:31.460 --> 00:35:32.460
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: Mm-hmm.

00:35:32.460 --> 00:35:36.470
&gt;&gt;Male #1: And for a couple of episodes now,
they've invited you to do a Story Sync.

00:35:36.470 --> 00:35:37.520
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: Yep.

00:35:37.520 --> 00:35:42.950
&gt;&gt;Male #1: Which of the, either programs or
networks, are doing that most effectively

00:35:42.950 --> 00:35:46.769
from an advertiser perspective? Like, the
ones that are most advertiser friendly.

00:35:46.769 --> 00:35:51.410
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: Yup. I would say the NBCU
cable networks and AMC are probably doing

00:35:51.410 --> 00:35:56.710
the most in that space right now and have
had the most success from an advertiser standpoint.

00:35:56.710 --> 00:36:01.339
And again, I talked before about there's some
programs that lend themselves to this better

00:36:01.339 --> 00:36:06.420
than others. So, just because a network isn't
doing it well, may mean that they just don't

00:36:06.420 --> 00:36:08.029
have the right programming to do this with.

00:36:08.029 --> 00:36:11.721
So, "Walking Dead" has a very cult following.
There's a lot of interesting stuff you can

00:36:11.721 --> 00:36:18.990
do with zombies and that kind of stuff. And
Bravo has all kinds of reality programming

00:36:18.990 --> 00:36:25.130
that lends itself to companion content. They
have digital story-telling now. Their whole

00:36:25.130 --> 00:36:29.529
transmedia play that is bringing people back
onto the shows.

00:36:29.529 --> 00:36:33.999
So, I think their programming lends itself
well and they've been experimenting a lot

00:36:33.999 --> 00:36:37.589
in this area. And they've probably been the
most successful to date.

00:36:37.589 --> 00:36:38.589
&gt;&gt;Male #1: Thanks.

00:36:38.589 --> 00:36:39.589
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: Mm-hmm.

00:36:39.589 --> 00:36:41.969
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: There's a question back
there with Aaron. And if you have questions,

00:36:41.969 --> 00:36:44.009
please go to the mics just so that they can
be recorded.

00:36:44.009 --> 00:36:50.630
&gt;&gt;Male #2: Hi, Stacey. There's a lot of data,
a lot of publicity around the number of tweets

00:36:50.630 --> 00:36:54.630
around certain ads, certain programs, etcetera.
And then sometimes, you hear some mention

00:36:54.630 --> 00:36:59.210
about sentiment, whether it's positive or
negative. Have you seen much evidence that

00:36:59.210 --> 00:37:02.680
the data that goes beyond that is of high
quality?

00:37:02.680 --> 00:37:09.390
So, for example, can you tell from the tweets,
demographics or interests, things like that?

00:37:09.390 --> 00:37:13.410
Have you seen that sort of data? What is the
quality of that data? I guess my second question

00:37:13.410 --> 00:37:18.369
would be, do you feel like there's any sort
of bias among the people that are tweeting

00:37:18.369 --> 00:37:20.820
that you have to discount when you're analyzing
this information?

00:37:20.820 --> 00:37:26.529
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: Yeah. So, Bluefin's done
a lot with sentiment. And sentiment's hard

00:37:26.529 --> 00:37:33.520
to measure. We did some testing with them
and found that things weren't allocated correctly

00:37:33.520 --> 00:37:37.690
to positive or negative sentiments. So, I
think we--. You really have to look at that

00:37:37.690 --> 00:37:44.000
stuff closely. But there are a lot of these
algorithms that are being built that are getting

00:37:44.000 --> 00:37:53.719
at stuff that's pretty valuable to us, that
the male/female of who's tweeting, age--general.

00:37:53.719 --> 00:38:00.180
So, I think we are getting more specifics
about who those people are. I mean, I think

00:38:00.180 --> 00:38:06.559
we know that the people who are tweeting are
not the minority , right? They're not as large

00:38:06.559 --> 00:38:11.290
of an audience as what we're getting on TV,
but they're pretty influential. We don't really

00:38:11.290 --> 00:38:16.019
know how many people they're really reaching
with what they're saying.

00:38:16.019 --> 00:38:24.119
But we have to pay close attention to it because
they have a pretty powerful impact on our

00:38:24.119 --> 00:38:30.400
brands. If they're talking about our brands
and they are saying great things and saying,

00:38:30.400 --> 00:38:37.330
"Oh, you should try it," that's somebody who's
sought out these social impressions. And that's

00:38:37.330 --> 00:38:41.719
a pretty valuable thing. So, we want to create
environments where people can have that kind

00:38:41.719 --> 00:38:44.150
of conversation about our brands.

00:38:44.150 --> 00:38:47.089
But I think there's still more to learn. We
don't know everything about who those people

00:38:47.089 --> 00:38:52.819
are who are tweeting. And it is hard to filter
out some of the stuff you're talking about.

00:38:52.819 --> 00:38:53.819
[pause]

00:38:53.819 --> 00:38:54.819
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: Question over here.

00:38:54.819 --> 00:38:55.819
&gt;&gt;Female #2: Yeah. Hi.

00:38:55.819 --> 00:38:56.819
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: Hi.

00:38:56.819 --> 00:39:03.460
&gt;&gt;Female #2: I read a quote this morning,
Marc Pritchard of P and G, talking about the

00:39:03.460 --> 00:39:08.509
importance of building one-on-one relationships
with customers around the globe and essentially

00:39:08.509 --> 00:39:12.380
pointing towards a trend of spending less
on broadcast and more on mobile and social.

00:39:12.380 --> 00:39:13.380
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: Mm-hmm.

00:39:13.380 --> 00:39:16.529
&gt;&gt;Female #2: And I'm just curious to what
extant--. Obviously, they are a global brand

00:39:16.529 --> 00:39:22.710
or have a number of global brands, but are
you seeing that pressure from people really

00:39:22.710 --> 00:39:25.700
shifting heavily on the budgets towards mobile
and social?

00:39:25.700 --> 00:39:30.680
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: I wouldn't say "shifting
heavily." I mean, P and G is huge brand with

00:39:30.680 --> 00:39:37.809
huge budgets that has the opportunity to shift
a little and not have a major impact. I definitely

00:39:37.809 --> 00:39:44.009
see the--. I mean, as more people are using
these different devices, then we need to find

00:39:44.009 --> 00:39:46.249
ways to market to them appropriately in those
devices.

00:39:46.249 --> 00:39:52.880
So, the more people who have mobile phones
and are using mobile phones to transact and

00:39:52.880 --> 00:39:56.670
go to stores and do all these things, and
we need to find ways to market to them there.

00:39:56.670 --> 00:40:01.400
So, you will be seeing more dollars shifting
in that area, and social as well. I mean,

00:40:01.400 --> 00:40:06.390
all the things we're talking about, there's
just more ways to reach your audience in social

00:40:06.390 --> 00:40:09.579
and there are powerful people that we need
to reach.

00:40:09.579 --> 00:40:14.349
So, you will some shift. I don't know that
when you say "major," I don't know that you're

00:40:14.349 --> 00:40:19.559
gonna see 20 percent shifts, 25 percent shifts
in dollars, but you are gonna see some dollars

00:40:19.559 --> 00:40:21.019
moving in that area.

00:40:21.019 --> 00:40:22.019
[pause]

00:40:22.019 --> 00:40:24.240
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: Back over here.

00:40:24.240 --> 00:40:30.269
&gt;&gt;Female #3: Hi. Beyond Twitter and Facebook,
have you seen other social platforms being

00:40:30.269 --> 00:40:36.279
utilized effectively by programmers and advertising,
advertisers, the Foursquares, the Pinterest,

00:40:36.279 --> 00:40:37.930
the Instagrams of the world?

00:40:37.930 --> 00:40:41.739
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: Yeah. I haven't seen--.
Pinterest is probably something we should

00:40:41.739 --> 00:40:47.509
watch because I think you're gonna see more
with it now. Definitely like the GetGlues

00:40:47.509 --> 00:40:54.299
and Misos and IntoNows and all the check-ins,
I think are being used in a good way. GetGlue

00:40:54.299 --> 00:40:58.880
has done a lot of, has a lot of relationships
with the networks and they're doing some really

00:40:58.880 --> 00:41:01.329
interesting things with retailers and offers.

00:41:01.329 --> 00:41:06.010
So, I think we've seen some success in that
area. And I think we talk about Twitter just

00:41:06.010 --> 00:41:11.279
because it's easy for us to measure and follow
Twitter, right? So, we probably talk about

00:41:11.279 --> 00:41:17.329
them more even though there's more people
on Facebook, fans of all of these shows, but

00:41:17.329 --> 00:41:21.509
we just don't have as much information about
them. Those are the two dominant ones, but

00:41:21.509 --> 00:41:23.859
there's definitely others that are having
impact.

00:41:23.859 --> 00:41:24.859
[pause]

00:41:24.859 --> 00:41:26.059
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: Back here.

00:41:26.059 --> 00:41:30.759
&gt;&gt;Male #3: Yeah. Kind of going off that, we
were talking about bringing television into

00:41:30.759 --> 00:41:35.549
the social experience. But is there a reverse
of the television experience coming into social--?

00:41:35.549 --> 00:41:39.809
Like, partnering with Time Warner Cable. Almost
doing like a user match, like "we know this

00:41:39.809 --> 00:41:44.680
person is watching such and such right now.
Why are not we not syncing up ads with that?"

00:41:44.680 --> 00:41:45.680
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: Mm-hmm.

00:41:45.680 --> 00:41:48.970
&gt;&gt;Male #3: So, is there experimentation going
on with that or what have you seen?

00:41:48.970 --> 00:41:53.979
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: Yeah. I mean, I think the
big thing that we're seeing, or the big need

00:41:53.979 --> 00:41:59.329
that we're seeing across, is the need for
single-source measurement. So, the ability

00:41:59.329 --> 00:42:04.640
to be able to measure all media in a way that
it's comparable.

00:42:04.640 --> 00:42:09.930
So, television measurement and impressions
have been around for a really long time--the

00:42:09.930 --> 00:42:15.559
CPNs and GRPEs--and moving towards that in
these other spaces is probably the place where

00:42:15.559 --> 00:42:20.059
you see we're trying to sync up as most. There's
definitely testing going on in that space.

00:42:20.059 --> 00:42:25.400
I'm not familiar with any particular example,
but I definitely think you'll see some testing

00:42:25.400 --> 00:42:26.400
in that area.

00:42:26.400 --> 00:42:27.400
[pause]

00:42:27.400 --> 00:42:28.400
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: Back here.

00:42:28.400 --> 00:42:32.119
&gt;&gt;Male #4: An example of combining old technology
and new technology--. I'm asking for a friend

00:42:32.119 --> 00:42:35.579
who just can't seem, my friend, Ellis, , who
can't seem to find the document to ask. So,

00:42:35.579 --> 00:42:40.569
forgive me if I'm losing the question in translation.
But Ellie was curious to know that as you

00:42:40.569 --> 00:42:44.609
talk about shifting budgets, is this interesting
to clients because it's social or because

00:42:44.609 --> 00:42:48.459
this is a digital of measurement. In essence,
a digital layer applied to a television, which

00:42:48.459 --> 00:42:52.269
traditionally, it doesn't offer the degree
of granular measurement that digital sometimes

00:42:52.269 --> 00:42:53.269
does?

00:42:53.269 --> 00:42:57.529
Is the future demanding social elements as
added value for TV buys, or are people warming

00:42:57.529 --> 00:43:00.640
to the idea of buying digital content to cover
off devices?

00:43:00.640 --> 00:43:04.450
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: OK. There were a lot of
questions there. So, the one that connected

00:43:04.450 --> 00:43:06.950
with me the most was, "Do clients want it
as added value?"

00:43:06.950 --> 00:43:07.950
&gt;&gt;Male #4: Sure.

00:43:07.950 --> 00:43:09.279
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: Of course they do.

00:43:09.279 --> 00:43:10.279
[laughter]

00:43:10.279 --> 00:43:16.390
Without a doubt. I mean, they still want digital
as added value for our television buys. So,

00:43:16.390 --> 00:43:19.209
it's hard to get clients to pay for something
that they don't know what they're getting

00:43:19.209 --> 00:43:26.709
for it, right? So, the measurement piece of
it is important. Go back to the first part

00:43:26.709 --> 00:43:29.650
of your question.

00:43:29.650 --> 00:43:34.660
&gt;&gt;Male #4: Is this interesting to clients
because it's social or because it's digital

00:43:34.660 --> 00:43:35.680
with measurement?

00:43:35.680 --> 00:43:42.140
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: It's interesting to clients
because it's, you can see the power that these

00:43:42.140 --> 00:43:49.079
people are having in this space. So, it's
people are choosing to interact with your

00:43:49.079 --> 00:43:54.150
brand. So, whether it's Facebook fans or people
talking about it or voting or whatever it

00:43:54.150 --> 00:43:58.180
is, we look at these as choice-based impressions,
right?

00:43:58.180 --> 00:44:03.829
People who are seeking out to comment, talk,
and engage with your brand. So, that's why

00:44:03.829 --> 00:44:08.249
it's important to them because these people
have a lot of influence on other people. So

00:44:08.249 --> 00:44:11.579
that's why they're paying attention because
it's getting to a scale that they need to

00:44:11.579 --> 00:44:12.579
pay attention to it.

00:44:12.579 --> 00:44:13.769
&gt;&gt;Male #4: So, let me ask a follow-up question
to that.

00:44:13.769 --> 00:44:14.769
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: Yeah.

00:44:14.769 --> 00:44:19.279
&gt;&gt;Male #4: How do assign a value then, to
a tweet or a like, or any of these interactions?

00:44:19.279 --> 00:44:22.049
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: Yeah. I don't know that
I have the answer to that. That's what we're

00:44:22.049 --> 00:44:25.829
trying to figure out. What is the value of
that when you don't know how many people it's

00:44:25.829 --> 00:44:28.920
really reaching? I don't know the answer,
but we're working on it.

00:44:28.920 --> 00:44:29.920
[pause]

00:44:29.920 --> 00:44:31.049
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: Back here?

00:44:31.049 --> 00:44:32.329
&gt;&gt;Male #5: Hi.

00:44:32.329 --> 00:44:33.609
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: Hi.

00:44:33.609 --> 00:44:38.420
&gt;&gt;Male #5: From the examples you gave in the
interactions that you see and that you're

00:44:38.420 --> 00:44:42.890
trying to measure socially, it seems like
this is all dependent upon the programming

00:44:42.890 --> 00:44:46.549
being synchronously live, like happening at
the same time. A lot of people are seeing

00:44:46.549 --> 00:44:50.099
it at the same time. Is that a fair assessment?

00:44:50.099 --> 00:44:55.640
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: I mean, a lot of it happens
live--people watching it. So, you're asking

00:44:55.640 --> 00:44:59.269
what happens in a DVR environment or when
people aren't watching it at the same time?

00:44:59.269 --> 00:45:00.269
Is it as relevant to them?

00:45:00.269 --> 00:45:01.269
&gt;&gt;Male #5: Yeah. That's where I was going.

00:45:01.269 --> 00:45:02.269
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: Yeah.

00:45:02.269 --> 00:45:03.269
&gt;&gt;Male #5: Yeah.

00:45:03.269 --> 00:45:08.470
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: So, yes and no. I think
that the content creators are trying to figure

00:45:08.470 --> 00:45:13.700
out how to make sure that all of this works
in a DVR environment so it doesn't have to

00:45:13.700 --> 00:45:17.499
happen live. I mean, with the voting stuff,
it has to happen within two hours.

00:45:17.499 --> 00:45:22.910
So, it somewhat has to happen live. But there
are other things that are being created that

00:45:22.910 --> 00:45:29.109
don't have to happen right within that hour
time period. And that will allow you the couple

00:45:29.109 --> 00:45:34.200
of days to watch the show and be a part of
it. So, I think they understand that they

00:45:34.200 --> 00:45:37.849
need to create it in a way that it would work
in a time-shifted environment as well.

00:45:37.849 --> 00:45:38.849
&gt;&gt;Male #5: OK. Thanks.

00:45:38.849 --> 00:45:39.849
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: Yup.

00:45:39.849 --> 00:45:40.849
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: Back here.

00:45:40.849 --> 00:45:41.849
&gt;&gt;Male #6: Hi. How are you?

00:45:41.849 --> 00:45:42.849
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: I'm good.

00:45:42.849 --> 00:45:45.999
&gt;&gt;Male #6: My name's Matt. I think there's
a number of folks here work in a sales capacity

00:45:45.999 --> 00:45:51.269
at Google. And I'd just be curious, maybe
you could give us a little advice. I think

00:45:51.269 --> 00:45:57.569
social TV is probably a challenging sell because
it feels somewhat unpredictable to a client.

00:45:57.569 --> 00:46:02.430
I guess, both in the fact that you present
them the idea of social and maybe they'd be

00:46:02.430 --> 00:46:04.769
like, "Well, what are they gonna say about
my brand?"

00:46:04.769 --> 00:46:09.230
That's unpredictable. But also, I'm used to
putting in money and getting out impressions

00:46:09.230 --> 00:46:13.490
in a very linear, planned way throughout the
course of the year. And that creates the things

00:46:13.490 --> 00:46:18.690
I expect to be created at the time I expect
it. And so, social TV has both those--or social

00:46:18.690 --> 00:46:21.480
in general--has both those risks to them.

00:46:21.480 --> 00:46:22.480
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: Mm-hmm.

00:46:22.480 --> 00:46:24.579
&gt;&gt;Male #6: So, when you're talking to risk
adverse clients--

00:46:24.579 --> 00:46:25.579
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: Yeah.

00:46:25.579 --> 00:46:28.709
&gt;&gt;Male #6: we'd love to hear some of the tricks
that you use and some of the ways you sell.

00:46:28.709 --> 00:46:32.390
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: So, one of the things I've
been--. There's probably two really important

00:46:32.390 --> 00:46:38.009
things as we're selling these social TV programs
through to our clients. The first is, we know

00:46:38.009 --> 00:46:41.719
that it costs a lot of money to produce this
additional content, right? It's not free to

00:46:41.719 --> 00:46:46.920
create all of this companion content to the
programming, to build the relationships with

00:46:46.920 --> 00:46:48.930
GetGlue, and all of these other things.

00:46:48.930 --> 00:46:54.059
But if the networks or content creators are
gonna try and pass all of those costs onto

00:46:54.059 --> 00:46:59.789
us, on the advertiser, it's not gonna happen
because we don't really know what we're getting

00:46:59.789 --> 00:47:06.250
out of it. So, there has to be a relationship
there where we're in this together and we're

00:47:06.250 --> 00:47:09.079
trying to figure it out together. So that's
one.

00:47:09.079 --> 00:47:13.969
And then, the second thing is building in
measurement where we can figure out whether

00:47:13.969 --> 00:47:18.560
this is really working or not because clients
are only gonna test for so long. And if we

00:47:18.560 --> 00:47:23.991
can't figure out if this is really working
and having an impact on the brand, then they're

00:47:23.991 --> 00:47:28.799
not gonna keep doing it. So, I would say those
are the two keys when we're, what we need

00:47:28.799 --> 00:47:32.400
from media partner as we're presenting these
to our clients.

00:47:32.400 --> 00:47:37.020
&gt;&gt;Male #6: Cool. And just a quick follow-up.
Do you find that to be predictable, do you

00:47:37.020 --> 00:47:42.259
find the outcomes that you expect generally
happen for clients, or do you find that it's

00:47:42.259 --> 00:47:45.809
all over the board what winds up happening
in a social TV campaign?

00:47:45.809 --> 00:47:53.839
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: I think some of it is predictable
and some things work and some things don't.

00:47:53.839 --> 00:48:00.269
I'm trying to think of a specific example
of--. I think, intuitively, when we did the

00:48:00.269 --> 00:48:05.769
synced ad test, and we haven't done it in
reality yet. We're getting there with one

00:48:05.769 --> 00:48:08.969
of our clients. And they do it in very near
future.

00:48:08.969 --> 00:48:15.709
I think, intuitively, we knew that a synced
ad would bring it back up at least from that

00:48:15.709 --> 00:48:20.819
second group that've seen a completely different
ad, but we didn't know it was gonna come back

00:48:20.819 --> 00:48:27.180
up as high as it did. So, if we're learning
things like that, those are gonna be big wins

00:48:27.180 --> 00:48:33.749
to be able to measure things like that. So,
I would say, intuitively, a lot is reaffirmed,

00:48:33.749 --> 00:48:38.039
but we're definitely learning and finding
things that aren't what we expected.

00:48:38.039 --> 00:48:39.469
&gt;&gt;Male #6: Thank you very much.

00:48:39.469 --> 00:48:40.469
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: Mm-hmm.

00:48:40.469 --> 00:48:41.469
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: This one.

00:48:41.469 --> 00:48:44.949
&gt;&gt;Male #7: Hi. First, I have a couple thoughts
on TV versus social media that I wanna get

00:48:44.949 --> 00:48:49.900
your feedback on. I think one of the reason
why TV will stay powerful for a long time,

00:48:49.900 --> 00:48:54.380
because I think it delivered the content in
a very scheduled way and a centralized way,

00:48:54.380 --> 00:48:56.589
whereas social media is very real-time.

00:48:56.589 --> 00:49:02.449
But the information is also very scattered
and very chaotic. And so, when people are

00:49:02.449 --> 00:49:07.109
consuming the product, the information, in
a very segmented way, people are still looking

00:49:07.109 --> 00:49:15.019
for a real live event, almost in a way that,
say, I know that on Sunday night at 9 PM that

00:49:15.019 --> 00:49:18.839
I can watch "The Walking Dead." And then,
I can have some event I can talk about.

00:49:18.839 --> 00:49:19.839
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: Right.

00:49:19.839 --> 00:49:22.190
&gt;&gt;Male #7: So, basis of the social needs of
people want to get it together,--

00:49:22.190 --> 00:49:23.190
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: Right.

00:49:23.190 --> 00:49:25.539
&gt;&gt;Male #7: but social media wouldn't be able
to provide that. Do you think that's--?

00:49:25.539 --> 00:49:28.489
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: Yeah. I agree with you.
I think the way Mike and I talk about it is

00:49:28.489 --> 00:49:32.950
TV has always been social. It's just now,
you can talk about it instantly, right? So

00:49:32.950 --> 00:49:37.049
before, you used to go into work the next
day and you have that water cooler, right?

00:49:37.049 --> 00:49:40.200
It was a water cooler shows, those NBC comedies,
"Seinfeld" or whatever.

00:49:40.200 --> 00:49:45.079
You talk about it with your friends the next
day. We talk about social media, and now it's

00:49:45.079 --> 00:49:49.910
your virtual water cooler. You have the ability
to talk to people about it right then in that

00:49:49.910 --> 00:49:55.579
moment, or within a period of time, about
the experience that you're having or have

00:49:55.579 --> 00:50:00.969
just had. So, I don't think it's a huge shift
in behavior, which is why I don't think television

00:50:00.969 --> 00:50:04.160
is dying because people have always behaved
this way.

00:50:04.160 --> 00:50:07.599
Now, they just have a different outlet to
do it--a more instant outlet to do it.

00:50:07.599 --> 00:50:11.769
&gt;&gt;Male #7: Right. So, that leads to my second
question, which is when it comes to implementing

00:50:11.769 --> 00:50:17.799
the social media content, do you think the
agencies are shifting of updating real-time

00:50:17.799 --> 00:50:24.220
to say, do a bit of content almost the same
way as how TV people do the content? Like,

00:50:24.220 --> 00:50:29.210
every Tuesday I'm gonna post this kind of
content. Every Wednesday--. Do you think that

00:50:29.210 --> 00:50:31.759
will be some of the best practice that we'll
do, or--?

00:50:31.759 --> 00:50:35.170
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: You know, I don't know
because we hear so much about content needing

00:50:35.170 --> 00:50:42.309
to be on-demand and moving away from a schedule.
So, I don't get the sense that the content

00:50:42.309 --> 00:50:47.789
is being created and delivered on a schedule
in the digital space. So, I'm not sure that

00:50:47.789 --> 00:50:51.279
it's gonna be created that way because I think
that they want people to be able to access

00:50:51.279 --> 00:50:54.680
it whenever they wanna access it.

00:50:54.680 --> 00:50:59.539
But I think you're right. I mean, I think
there's this reassurance in knowing that there

00:50:59.539 --> 00:51:04.440
is a television schedule and people know when
things are gonna be on. And they set their

00:51:04.440 --> 00:51:10.630
DVRs or they watch it on VOD, or they watch
it on Hulu or Full Episode Play or within

00:51:10.630 --> 00:51:14.400
a certain amount of time because they wanna
be able to talk about it and experience it

00:51:14.400 --> 00:51:15.400
with someone else.

00:51:15.400 --> 00:51:18.470
So, I'm not sure that digital is gonna be
on that same schedule.

00:51:18.470 --> 00:51:19.520
&gt;&gt;Male #7: OK.

00:51:19.520 --> 00:51:21.329
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: What do you think?

00:51:21.329 --> 00:51:25.769
&gt;&gt;Male #7: I think it will eventually. And
I think that's what YouTube is trying to do.

00:51:25.769 --> 00:51:26.769
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: Yes.

00:51:26.769 --> 00:51:31.190
&gt;&gt;Male #7: They're trying to mock what TV
is doing and have a set schedule, set channel.

00:51:31.190 --> 00:51:34.819
And I think that's how media is always evolving
after discovering--.

00:51:34.819 --> 00:51:36.569
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: It makes it easier to find.

00:51:36.569 --> 00:51:40.619
&gt;&gt;Male #7: Yeah. Like, how TV channels used
to start with one channel with every program.

00:51:40.619 --> 00:51:42.940
Then, they have different content for different
industry.

00:51:42.940 --> 00:51:43.940
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: Yeah.

00:51:43.940 --> 00:51:47.519
&gt;&gt;Male #7: Yeah. And my last question. I promise
it's the last one.

00:51:47.519 --> 00:51:48.519
[Stacey Shepatin laughs]

00:51:48.519 --> 00:51:53.949
So, I think for branding, it's a lot related
to how emotionally the consumer would be bonded

00:51:53.949 --> 00:51:54.949
to the brands.

00:51:54.949 --> 00:51:55.949
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: Yep.

00:51:55.949 --> 00:51:58.880
&gt;&gt;Male #7: And when you, when it comes to
social media, do you think--? I think it's

00:51:58.880 --> 00:52:03.109
still in the very early stage that it can,
you really affect how people are emotionally

00:52:03.109 --> 00:52:05.059
perceive the brand. What do you think of that?

00:52:05.059 --> 00:52:08.759
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: Yeah. I would agree with
you. I think that's what I'm, why when I was

00:52:08.759 --> 00:52:14.339
talking about before, you can have a big impact
on how people perceive your brand. So, we

00:52:14.339 --> 00:52:18.519
need to pay attention to what people are saying
and make sure we're marketing appropriately

00:52:18.519 --> 00:52:22.839
to them, to at least create an environment
for them to talk positively about your brand.

00:52:22.839 --> 00:52:27.829
&gt;&gt;Male #7: Do you have any specific measurement
that you can use to measure against how emotionally

00:52:27.829 --> 00:52:30.269
that impact on the brands on the consumers?

00:52:30.269 --> 00:52:31.579
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: How measurement--?

00:52:31.579 --> 00:52:36.170
&gt;&gt;Male #7: What kind of measurement that you
are using to measure against how emotionally

00:52:36.170 --> 00:52:40.630
that the information can have influence on
the brands when it comes to social media?

00:52:40.630 --> 00:52:46.450
&gt;&gt;Stacey Shepatin: So, we're working on putting
those kinds of research tools in place to

00:52:46.450 --> 00:52:50.509
be able to figure out what kind of impact
that social conversation is having on our

00:52:50.509 --> 00:52:53.609
brands. So, we're working through that now.
I'm not sure what all the companies are that

00:52:53.609 --> 00:52:54.849
we're using to get there.

00:52:54.849 --> 00:52:58.489
But there's a lot of companies in this space
that are measuring what people are saying.

00:52:58.489 --> 00:53:03.700
And we just need to put it together in a way
that it's usable for our clients.

00:53:03.700 --> 00:53:04.700
&gt;&gt;Male #7: Thank you.

00:53:04.700 --> 00:53:08.630
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: OK. And I think we have
a final question before we have to wrap up.

00:53:08.630 --> 00:53:12.019
&gt;&gt;Female #4: I'll just wrap it up. Actually,
he got a lot of my questions, too, but so

00:53:12.019 --> 00:53:17.579
I have a new one. [laughs] I'm sure it's probably
